Update owing to @GMR & @belikewater

Total Omicron cases sequenced to date: 45,145, including another 8,044 today. So for next week's report up to 22nd December we should be at 61-69k total, based on past weeks throughput capacity, and the proportion of sequenced cases that are Omicron is increasing. Total SGTF cases now at 124,954, after adding over 25k today, so with these 'probable' cases it would be game over already. As an indicator, SGTF cases were at 62.85% Omicron on 15th, climbing at approx 5% per day. Even if the sequencing rate drops to an average 10k per day (in total), then at anything over 70% prevalence for Omicron should clear 100k around 28-29th December. This is without any 'probable' cases. I think there will undoubtedly be a few days with lower counts due to staff shortages through holidays and illness, but while only 4 lighthouse labs test for SGTF, sequencing is carried out through a large network comprised of NHS organisations, the four Public Health Agencies of the UK, the Wellcome Sanger Institute and twelve academic partners, which should help average out daily capacity to some degree. It is perhaps not an absolute certainty at this point, but we should be 4-9k ahead of the doubtful range imho for 22nd December, so I'll hold and monitor for now.

I was going to comment on the curiosity of SGTF to this question. How SGTF testing is only used in four lighthouse laboratories around the UK and therefore is not reliable for providing a geographic representation of Omicron due to regional dead spots, but still very valuable to gauge the speed of spread and prevalence. UKHSA now list confirmed cases (via whole-genome sequencing or genotyping) and SGTF cases, on their daily overview: cumulative data, but while SGTF is not included in that total confirmed and probable set (yet), they do list SGTF as 'probable' cases via the Daily Briefing report Summary... curious. Anyway, I was going to comment on that, then I saw that over 10k cases have just been reported as confirmed in a single day. 10,059 for a total of 24,968. So sequencing capacity appears to have increased, compared to previous weekly high of 64k. SGTF cases were at 62.85% on 15th, climbing from 56.91% on 14th. These indicators suggest the total will exceed 100k within 12 days, even with a drop in sequencing over holiday periods.

Rethinking. 61k samples were sequenced (not genotyped) in the week starting Nov 28, and probably ~64k were sequenced in the week starting Dec 5 (projecting forward): https://sars2.cvr.gla.ac.uk/cog-uk/ They have not been using their standard genotyping assay with Omicron, presumably because just looking for SGTF or 69-70 deletion is a lot easier. They may not use their usual genotyping assay at all. If they start reporting SGTF/69-70 deletion samples (now considered probable cases) in the data used to resolve this question, it will resolve next week. If they only report sequences, then it is trickier. Perhaps we can expect ~70% of sequenced samples in the data reported Dec 24 to be Omicron. Let's say 65k sequences * 0.7 = 45k Omicron. 45k + 10k = 55k. Nearly all sequences in the final report of the year will be Omicron. But how much will they sequence that week? If next week comes in at ~55k (sequence data only), then I'll lower my forecast, as I don't want to rely on sequences to get us to 100k during the holidays. But I'm going to bet that they'll start reporting probable cases.

Time to update my previous estimate. - official data to 8th Dec ( https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-variants-genomically-confirmed-case-numbers/variants-distribution-of-case-data-10-december-2021 ) has 568 cases, up from 32 to 1st Dec (18x in 7 days). - current total in the news is 4,713 ( https://news.sky.com/story/covid-19-uk-reports-another-1-576-cases-of-omicron-variant-12495009 ), up from 134 nine days before (35x in 9 days) - I had allowed a 10% chance it doesn't become widespread in the UK. That was probably an over-estimate at the time, in any case the chance now is zero. - I had assumed a doubling time of 3-6 days. It now looks clear the doubling time is around 2 days (or the official 2.4 days?), at least in the short term. - so from 568 cases to 8th Dec, we can extrapolate 100,000 cases reached in 14-18 days (22nd - 26th Dec), assuming it doesn't slow down. - it will of course slow down - due to measures, or due to caution, or at some point naturally. But I suspect we'll blow past 100K cases before such things have much effect. - estimate 21st - 31st Dec.

When will 100k samples will be genetically characterized as Omicron (confirmed using sequencing, or probable using genotyping)? There were 568 as of December 8th [1], and 4713 confirmed as of December 13th [2]. SGTF is being used to guide additional sequencing [3], but only about 40k samples are sequenced each week. About 60k samples are genotyped each week, and it is unclear when genotyping will be used to identify Omicron. Stealth Omicron [4] would seem to rule out just using the simple SGTF criteria. Specific genotyping assays to detect the Omicron variant are available [5,6], but might take time to add to workflow.

If SGTF is included as probable at some point, with >3000 cases and a 2.5 days doubling time, it seems highly likely we will hit 100k. However SGTF is NOT currently included (see https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/covid-19-variants-genomically-confirmed-case-numbers/variants-distribution-of-case-data-10-december-2021) meaning that the number used to resolve this question is running at about a 1/6 of the SGTF number. Assuming a 3 day doubling time would still see us reach 100k by the end of the month on this measure.

New total now in: 568 total Omicron results sequenced (536 added the week to 8th December), quite close to expected. Also significant is that the total number sequenced (and genotyped!) this week was over 111,000. So this rate has increased and will reflect in higher total numbers of Omicron as it gains prevalence. For example if Omicron reaches 50% prevalence by 28th December, the total number of sequenced and genotyped results for that week could now be >55k. So the cumulative total could well be 10-20% higher than based on my earlier estimate for sequencing capacity. To counter that, Delta cases are also rising, and continued prevalence of Delta will hold the proportion of sequenced Omicron cases back till Omicron gains dominance. Final note, the doubling rate 'should' slow slightly and will I think tend back towards 3.5 days as mandates start to take effect. With these noted, I'm marking expected totals as a tracker, dated to each report as: 17th December: 2.5-3.5k (total 3-4k), 24th December: 11-16k (total 14-20k), 31st December 45-65k (total 59-85k), 7th January total >100k

In order to hit 100k by Dec 30th, Omicron identification needs to maintain or exceed a steady 30% daily increase, hitting a maximum of 24,911 cases on December 28th. Today's total of 817 cases = a jump of 44% from yesterday's total. This may go down again, however with consistently reliable Prof. Christina Pagel (head of research, UCLH) projecting that Omicron will outrun Delta over the next couple of weeks leading to 100k cases per day by Christmas, only a fraction of these need to be identified daily to hit the first bin.

As from an earlier forecast, the outcome will partly be determined by the spread of Omicron, and partly by the rate of sequencing and how that changes each week. Currently capacity has never exceeded 100k/wk, but this could change. A small increase in both characterisation capacity and the doubling rate could just about get us to bin1. But more likely I think will be a marginal decrease in the doubling rate as Plan B gets pushed ahead (partly to cover up headlines on the Government’s Christmas parties last year - during lockdown). So I’m expecting Omicron at ~35% prevalence by year end, and a total of 45-60k sequenced results. This could all change in the first week of Jan, with 45-50k further sequenced results tipping the total over 100k total.

As always, note that this question isn't asking when there will 100k cases caused by Omicron, but when 100k cases will be genetically characterized (sequenced or genotyped) as Omicron. Each week, ~85k-110k samples are genetically characterized, and so each week, a fraction of those will be characterized as Omicron cases. If Omicron causes half of all cases in a given week, then about half of all samples characterized that week will be characterized as Omicron, regardless of how many more cases Omicron actually causes.

In the context of the various case counts; actual cases, reported cases, and genomically sequenced cases, on the basis that Omicron spreads faster than Delta (appears almost certain) then actual cases may top 200k by year end, and reported cases could well be near 100k. Still making bin1 very unlikely. What’s changed since the Delta wave is that genomic sequencing capacity and speed has increased, so the gap between sequenced cases and reported cases could be much smaller than we saw previously. I also suspect that S-gene target failure (SGTF) will increasingly be used as a more widespread method of detection, due to convenience, concerns about R and tracking community spread with minimal delays. Further mitigating factors are not likely in the very short term, at least in England, so I'm still estimating a doubling rate ~4-6 days (from ~3 currently). All leads me to believe we may hit 100k ‘confirmed or probable’ cases through genomic sequencing a week or two earlier than initially projected, making bin2 overwhelmingly likely. I’ll look for more evidence to back up this suspicion.

Omicron is pretty scary, it has lots of mysterious mutations and seems to be doing well in South Africa. There's some uncertainty to this because we don't yet have much data that tells us how dominant (or not) Omicron is against Delta, but preliminary data does suggest Omicron might well be dominant. With that in mind, as well as the currently high number of daily cases that is expected to remain high (and most likely, increase), it's only a matter of time until most (trending towards all) daily cases are Omicron cases. How long this takes will depend on how dominant Omicron is against Delta. For reference, Delta became dominant in less than two months and is considered ~1.5 times more likely to cause an infection compared to Alpha in the UK (https://www.publichealth.columbia.edu/public-health-now/news/delta-variant-60-percent-more-contagious-original-virus-and-evades-immunity). If this were to hold for Omicron vs Delta then it seems very likely that 100k cases (*confirmed or probable*) could be reached by the end of January. In particular, Delta appeared during spring, a period that included some restrictions, more outdoor activities and vaccines, as opposed to winter, which as we saw last year can accommodate many cases even if there are restrictions (although there were no vaccines last winter). If Omicron is not dominant over Delta e.g., if it is equally likely to cause an infection, then it could take a moderate amount of time to reach 100k cases (*confirmed or probable*) because Delta will remain the most probable source of infection for some time. If Delta remains the dominant variant then Omicron could disappear quite quickly, or at least occur very rarely in the confirmed or probable cases, as other variants of concern did in France for example once Delta became dominant. Because of the preliminary evidence indicating Omicron might spread much more than Delta, my initial outcome distribution is going to tend towards the end of January. https://twitter.com/TWenseleers/status/1465100337631608832 https://twitter.com/jburnmurdoch/status/1466480113487392769
